The paper focuses on the power and thermal characteristics of the Google Glass, which is a wearable device. This makes it likely to fall under the Human-Computer Interaction (cs.HC) category, as it deals with the interaction between humans and technology. Additionally, the paper discusses the energy consumption and heat dissipation of the device, which could fall under the Energy Technology (cs.ET) and Systems and Control (cs.SD) categories, respectively. The paper also uses the Glass as a case study for optical head-mounted display devices, which could fall under the Optical Engineering (cs.OH) category. Finally, the paper discusses the implications of their findings for the safety and utility of head-mounted devices, which could fall under the Augmented Reality (cs.AR) category.
